-- ── Catalyst ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Catalyst (catalyst.io) is a customer success platform built to help customer success and revenue teams centralize customer data, track account health, and drive retention and expansion. Important distinction: this Catalyst is an entirely different product from Catalyst by Zoho, the serverless backend-as-a-service platform covered separately in this directory; the two share only a name and have no corporate or technical relationship. This Catalyst was founded in 2017 in New York City by brothers Edward Chiu and Kevin Chiu and grew into a Series C company backed by roughly $63.4 million in funding from investors including Accel, Spark Capital, and Ludlow Ventures. In a significant development, Catalyst Software has merged with Totango, another prominent customer success platform, combining the two companies' technology to offer what they describe as more complete customer growth solutions for customer success and sales organizations. The platform integrates with a company's existing tool stack to give a single, unified view of customer health, usage, and engagement, enabling customer success managers to proactively intervene before churn happens rather than reacting after the fact. Notable customers cited by the company include SAP, GitHub, Schneider Electric, Dynatrace, Aircall, Braze, Fivetran, and Heap. Pricing is not publicly published; prospective customers must request a demo to receive a quote.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Custom, quote-based pricing (not publicly disclosed; requires a sales demo)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Contact for pricing (no public pricing tiers)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2017, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Mid-size, venture-backed (Series C funded; exact headcount not publicly disclosed) — now operating jointly with Totango following their merger$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$New York City, New York, US$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Catalyst (catalyst.io) Review 2026: Customer Success Platform Explained$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$What is Catalyst, the customer success platform behind catalyst.io? Features, the Totango merger, pricing, and how it differs from Catalyst by Zoho.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Catalyst, found at catalyst.io, is a customer success platform designed to help customer success, account management, and revenue teams centralize customer data and proactively manage account health to reduce churn and grow revenue. It is important to distinguish this Catalyst clearly from Catalyst by Zoho, a completely separate serverless backend-as-a-service and app development platform from Zoho Corporation; despite sharing the same name, these are unrelated products from unrelated companies serving entirely different purposes, one for customer success teams and one for software developers. This Catalyst was founded in 2017 in New York City by brothers Edward Chiu and Kevin Chiu, who built what the company describes as the most intuitive customer success platform on the market. Over its history the company raised approximately $63.4 million across funding rounds up to a Series C, from investors including Accel, Spark Capital, and Ludlow Ventures, positioning it among the more well-funded standalone customer success platforms. A major development in the company's trajectory was its merger with Totango, another established customer success platform vendor; together, the combined company positions itself as offering more powerful, unified customer growth solutions for customer success and sales teams, blending Catalyst's product with Totango's technology and customer base. Functionally, Catalyst is built around the idea of giving customer success managers a single, centralized view of every account by integrating with the other tools already in a company's stack, such as CRM, product analytics, support, and billing systems, so that usage trends, support tickets, health scores, and other signals live in one place rather than scattered across disconnected systems. This lets CS teams move from reactive account management to proactive intervention, for example receiving automated alerts when a customer stops using features considered critical to their long-term retention, so a customer success manager can reach out before the account is at serious churn risk. The platform serves customer success and revenue teams at business-to-business software companies, and its publicly cited customer list includes recognizable enterprise and mid-market names such as SAP, GitHub, Schneider Electric, Dynatrace, and Aircall, alongside revenue-focused brands like Braze, Fivetran, and Heap. Catalyst does not publish self-serve pricing tiers or a price list on its marketing site; like most enterprise customer success software, prospective customers must request a demo and go through a sales conversation to receive a customized quote, which is typical for B2B software in this category where pricing usually scales with number of managed accounts, users, or contract value. Because of the ambiguity created by other products also using the Catalyst name, most notably Zoho's developer platform, anyone researching this product should specifically look for catalyst.io or references to the Totango merger to confirm they are looking at the correct customer success company rather than the unrelated backend-as-a-service platform.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'a2641553-2df4-4aff-b662-314b0dddc12d';

