-- ── Catalyst by Zoho ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Catalyst by Zoho is Zoho Corporation's serverless, full-stack backend-as-a-service platform for building and hosting web and mobile applications without managing infrastructure. It is a completely different product from the standalone customer success platform simply called Catalyst (catalyst.io) also covered in this directory; the two share only a name, with no relationship between the two companies or products. Zoho first announced Catalyst publicly on October 17, 2019 as part of an initiative to open up the same internal infrastructure that powers Zoho's own suite of business applications, and the platform reached broader general availability in the years following. Catalyst provides Function-as-a-Service compute in Java and Node.js across five function types (basic I/O, advanced I/O, event functions, scheduled/periodic functions, and integration functions), alongside managed backend services like a relational data store, file storage, caching, authentication, and Zia-powered AI and ML capabilities such as OCR and object detection. Pricing follows a free-tier-forever model (more than 70 components included at no cost every month) plus a pay-as-you-go option with a $5 monthly minimum once free-tier limits are exceeded, and an optional subscription model for teams that prefer predictable monthly budgeting, starting from example plans around $25 to $30 per month. As part of Zoho Corporation, a large, privately held, profitable software company founded in 1996, Catalyst benefits from deep integration with the broader Zoho ecosystem of 55-plus business applications.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free tier plus pay-as-you-go (postpaid, $5 monthly minimum once free tier is exceeded), with an optional fixed-budget subscription model$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free tier available forever; paid usage begins around $5/month minimum, with example subscription plans starting near $25-30/month$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2019, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Large (product division of Zoho Corporation, a privately held company with 15,000+ employees globally)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Chennai, India and Austin, Texas, US (Zoho Corporation's dual headquarters)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Catalyst by Zoho Review 2026: Serverless Backend-as-a-Service Platform$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$A full review of Catalyst by Zoho, the serverless full-stack app development platform: features, pricing, pros and cons, and how it differs from the standalone Catalyst customer success tool.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Catalyst by Zoho is a serverless, full-stack backend-as-a-service and application development platform built by Zoho Corporation, designed to let developers build, host, and scale web and mobile applications without provisioning or managing their own servers. It is important to note this is an entirely different product from the standalone Catalyst customer success platform at catalyst.io, which is built by an unrelated company for customer success teams rather than developers; the shared name is coincidental and the two products have no technical or business relationship. Zoho publicly announced Catalyst on October 17, 2019, describing it as opening up the same internal serverless infrastructure that already powers Zoho's own suite of more than 55 business applications, such as Zoho CRM, Zoho Books, and Zoho Mail, so that outside developers could build on the same foundation. The platform reached general availability in the years following its initial announcement, with Zoho continuing to expand its capabilities through the early 2020s. At its core, Catalyst offers Function-as-a-Service compute supporting Java and Node.js, organized into five distinct function types: Basic I/O Functions for straightforward request-response logic, Advanced I/O Functions for streaming and parsing large payloads, Event Functions and Event Listeners triggered by specific application or platform events, periodic functions for scheduled or cron-style tasks, and Integration Functions built specifically to connect with other Zoho services. Beyond compute, Catalyst bundles a set of managed backend services that developers would otherwise need to stitch together themselves, including a relational Data Store, file storage, a caching layer, user authentication, and a workflow orchestration feature called Circuits for coordinating multi-step application logic. It also exposes Zia, Zoho's AI engine, giving developers access to prebuilt AI and machine learning capabilities such as optical character recognition and object detection without training their own models, plus SDKs for iOS, Android, and web to build fully custom client applications on top of the platform. On pricing, Catalyst uses a free-tier-forever model that includes more than 70 components at no cost every month, such as a documented allotment of serverless function compute (measured in GB-seconds), a couple of gigabytes of Data Store storage, and a batch of free cache requests, refreshed automatically each billing cycle. First-time users additionally receive a one-time $250 credit of free resources. Once free-tier limits are exceeded, billing defaults to a postpaid pay-as-you-go model with a $5 monthly minimum, charging only for resources actually consumed with no separate subscription fee; alternatively, teams that prefer predictable budgeting can choose a subscription model, where Zoho cites an example Basic plan around $25 per month that effectively becomes $30 per month worth of usage because Zoho adds an extra $5 of resources on top of the selected plan at no additional charge. Elastic auto-scaling, end-to-end security around function and service access, and cost efficiency (paying only for actual compute time rather than idle server capacity) are among Catalyst's core selling points, and because it is built and operated by Zoho Corporation, a large, profitable, privately held software company founded in 1996 with dual headquarters in Chennai, India and Austin, Texas, Catalyst benefits from tight integration with the rest of Zoho's application ecosystem alongside enterprise-grade infrastructure reliability.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '8cd7aefe-b8d8-4c44-99fd-8bd25c94179b';

